    "I tried to remember their voices. Not the exact words, but the quality of their voices. Mom's voice was soft and melodic, with a slight Japanese accent that got stronger when she was excited. Dad's voice was deep and calm, with a reassuring steadiness that made everything seem manageable. I tried to remember the sound of their laughter together, but it was like trying to remember a dream—fuzzy and fragmented and always just out of reach.",
    "The apartment was full of their things but empty of their presence. Dad's tools in the garage. Mom's books on the shelves. Yuna's room, exactly as she'd left it. These were the artifacts of a life that had stopped, frozen in time, and I was living in a museum of their lives, surrounded by ghosts, and I pretended it was home.",
    "I stopped going into their bedroom. I couldn't handle seeing their things, their clothes, their bed, their personal space. It was too intimate, too painful, too real. So I closed the door and pretended that room didn't exist. I lived in the rest of the apartment, avoiding the one place that still felt like them.",
    "The neighbors asked about them. Mrs. Sato from next door. Mr. Tanaka from down the hall. They were kind, but their questions were painful. 'How are you doing?' they'd ask, and I'd say 'fine' because that was the answer they wanted. They'd nod sympathetically and say 'let us know if you need anything,' and I'd say 'I will,' but I wouldn't. I wouldn't ask for help because asking for help meant admitting I couldn't do this alone, and I couldn't admit that.",
