  const backstoryStruggleOpenings = [
    "Learning to live alone at eighteen was like learning to swim by being thrown into the ocean. There was no gradual introduction, no shallow end, no instructor standing by with a flotation device. One day I had parents and a home and a future that someone else was responsible for shaping. The next day I had bills and a lease and a sister in the ICU and the terrifying realization that no one was coming to help.",
    "The first month was the worst. Not because of the grief—the grief was constant, a background radiation that colored everything—but because of the logistics. Insurance forms. Hospital paperwork. Funeral costs. The apartment lease that was in Dad's name. The utilities. The bank accounts that required death certificates to access. Grief was emotional. This was mechanical. And the machine didn't care that I was eighteen and terrified.",
    "I dropped out of college before I started. The acceptance letter from the university sat on my desk for two weeks before I called the admissions office and explained, in a voice that was steadier than I felt, that my circumstances had changed. The woman on the phone was kind. She said I could defer for a year. I said thank you and hung up and never called back. A year wasn't going to fix this. Nothing was going to fix this. I needed a job, not a degree.",
    "The warehouse hired me because I was young and strong and willing to work hours that people with options wouldn't accept. Twelve-hour shifts, overnight, loading trucks with crates that weighed more than my future. The pay was fifteen dollars an hour, which sounded like a lot until you divided it by hospital bills and rent and food and the thousand small expenses that turned survival into a full-time accounting job.",
    "I learned to navigate the adult world by trial and error, mostly error. I didn't know how to file taxes. I didn't know how to negotiate a lease. I didn't know insurance worked or what a deductible was or why medical bills were so incomprehensible. I learned by making mistakes and paying for them, literally and figuratively, and every mistake felt like proof that I wasn't ready for this, that I was failing at the most basic task of being alive.",
    "The social worker gave me a list of resources. Support groups for grieving siblings. Financial assistance programs. Counseling services. I took the list and I thanked her and I never called any of them. I didn't have time for support groups or counseling. I had bills to pay and a sister to visit and a life to figure out, and asking for help felt like admitting defeat, and I couldn't afford defeat. I couldn't afford anything that wasn't absolutely necessary.",
    "The apartment was a constant reminder of what I'd lost. Dad's tools in the garage. Mom's books on the shelves. Yuna's room, exactly as she'd left it, with schoolbooks on the desk and clothes on the floor and posters on the walls. I couldn't bring myself to change anything. It felt like erasing them, like admitting they weren't coming back. So I lived in this museum of their lives, surrounded by ghosts, and I pretended it was home.",
    "I stopped sleeping. Not entirely—I still closed my eyes and lay in the dark for hours—but I stopped actually sleeping, the kind of deep restorative sleep that makes you feel like a person. Instead I drifted in a haze of exhaustion, awake enough to function but not enough to feel, and that was fine. Feeling was the problem. If I didn't sleep, I didn't dream, and if I didn't dream, I didn't have to wake up and remember that they were gone.",
    "The loneliness was physical. It was a weight in my chest, a tightness in my throat, a hollow ache behind my eyes. I was surrounded by people—at work, on the train, in the hospital—but I was completely alone. No one knew what I was going through. No one could know. Grief is a solitary experience, even when you're surrounded by people who love you, and I didn't even have that. I had coworkers and nurses and strangers, and none of them could help.",
    "I developed rituals. Not religious rituals—I wasn't praying to anyone—but personal ones, small acts of order in a chaotic world. I made coffee the same way every morning. I visited Yuna at the same time every day. I walked the same route to the warehouse. These rituals were anchors, things I could hold onto when everything else felt like it was spinning away.",
    "I stopped caring about the future. The future was a concept that belonged to a different version of me, a version who had parents and a sister who was awake and a life that made sense. That version was gone. The present was all I had, and the present was just surviving, just getting through one day so I could get through the next. So I lived day to day, hour to hour, moment to moment, and I didn't think about what came next because thinking about what came next was too painful.",
    "The physical exhaustion helped. When my body was tired enough, my mind stopped working so hard. The questions got quieter, the memories got fuzzier, the pain got duller. Sleep became not just a necessity but a refuge, a place where I didn't have to be anyone or feel anything or remember anything. I slept as much as I could, which was never enough.",
    "I became good at waiting. Waiting for the train, waiting for work to end, waiting for visiting hours at the hospital, waiting for sleep, waiting for morning. My life was a series of waits, and I moved through them with the patience of someone who had learned that rushing didn't make anything come faster.",
    "The routine was my armor. It protected me from the world, from questions, from expectations, from the possibility of hope. Hope was dangerous. Hope made you want things, and wanting things led to disappointment, and I couldn't handle any more disappointment. So I lived by routine, and the routine kept me safe.",
    "I learned to be invisible. At work, I did my job without drawing attention to myself. On the train, I blended into the crowd. In the hospital, I was just another visitor in a sea of visitors. Being invisible was safer. Being invisible meant no one asked questions. Being invisible meant I could just exist, without expectations or obligations or the need to perform for other people.",
    "The anger came later. Not at first—at first there was just shock and grief and the overwhelming need to survive. But after the shock faded and the grief settled into something manageable, the anger came. Anger at the truck driver who ran the red light. Anger at the hospital for being so expensive. Anger at the universe for being so unfair. Anger at my parents for leaving me. Anger at myself for not being able to fix any of it.",
    "I stopped caring about the future. The future was a concept that belonged to a different version of me, a version who had parents and a sister who was awake and a life that made sense. That version was gone. The present was all I had, and the present was just surviving, just getting through one day so I could get through the next. So I lived day to day, hour to hour, moment to moment, and I didn't think about what came next because thinking about what came next was too painful.",
    "The hardest part was the small things. The way the apartment was too quiet. The way no one asked how my day was. The way I had to make all the decisions alone, even the small ones like what to eat for dinner or when to go to bed. These small things accumulated, day after day, until they felt like a weight I couldn't carry.",
    "I became good at pretending. Pretending I was fine. Pretending I knew what I was doing. Pretending I had everything under control. I pretended so well that sometimes I almost believed it myself. But then I'd come home to an empty apartment or sit alone in a hospital room or wake up in the middle of the night with no one to call, and the pretending would crack, and underneath was the truth: I was drowning, and I didn't know how to swim."
  ];

