  const backstoryHeadsetOpenings = [
    "I found the headset in a box of Dad's things. I was going through his workshop, sorting through tools and projects I didn't understand, and there it was—wrapped in bubble wrap, tucked in the back of a drawer. No note, no explanation, just the headset and a receipt dated three months before the accident. He'd bought it for me. He'd bought it and never told me, and now he was gone and I'd never know why.",
    "The headset was expensive. I looked it up online—five hundred dollars, plus tax, plus shipping. Dad had paid for overnight delivery. He'd wanted me to have it on launch day. He'd wanted me to be part of whatever this was. But he'd never given it to me. Maybe he was waiting for my birthday. Maybe he was waiting for the right moment. Maybe he'd just forgotten. I'd never know.",
    "I almost threw it away. That was my first instinct. I didn't want it. I didn't want anything that reminded me of Dad, of the accident, of the life we used to have. But I couldn't bring myself to do it. It was the last thing he'd ever bought for me. Throwing it away felt like throwing him away, like erasing the last piece of evidence that he'd existed, that he'd loved me.",
    "The headset sat on my desk for weeks. I looked at it every day, but I didn't touch it. It was like a bomb that might go off if I handled it wrong. A bomb made of grief and guilt and questions I couldn't answer. What did Dad want me to do with it? Why did he buy it? What was he trying to tell me? I didn't know. I didn't know anything anymore.",
    "I finally opened the box on a Tuesday night. I don't know why Tuesday. I don't know why that night. Maybe I was just tired of looking at it. Maybe I was just tired of wondering. I opened the box and took out the headset and it was heavier than I expected, sleek and black and impossibly advanced, like something from a science fiction movie.",
    "The headset was beautiful in a way that technology rarely is. Smooth curves, matte finish, no visible seams or screws. It looked like something that had been grown, not manufactured. The inside was lined with soft material that felt expensive against my fingers. Dad had bought the premium model, of course. He never did things halfway.",
    "I found the receipt in the bottom of the box. Three months before the accident. Five hundred dollars. Overnight shipping. He'd paid extra for gift wrapping, even though he'd never given it to me. The receipt had a note in his handwriting: 'For Kael - something to help you escape when you need to.' Escape. That was the word he'd used. Escape from what? From my life? From my grief? From the reality that he was gone?",
    "The headset came with a manual, but I didn't read it. I didn't need to. The technology was intuitive, designed to be used by anyone, regardless of technical expertise. I plugged it in, charged it, and watched the lights blink as it powered on. The interface appeared in my vision, floating in the air like a hologram. Welcome to Endless Realms, it said. Create your account.",
    "I created an account. I used my real name, because I didn't have the energy to invent a fake one. I chose a username—Kael—and a password—the same one I used for everything else. The system asked for my email address, my date of birth, my location. I answered the questions mechanically, without thinking, like I was filling out a form at the DMV.",
    "The character creation screen appeared. I could choose my race, my class, my appearance. I could be anyone I wanted. A warrior, a mage, a rogue. Human, elf, dwarf, orc. The possibilities were endless, but I didn't want endless possibilities. I wanted to be myself. I chose human, left the appearance settings on default, and selected the class that seemed most appropriate for someone who was tired and sad and alone: Vampire Progenitor.",
    "The system asked if I was sure. Vampire Progenitor was a rare class, it said. Difficult to master. High risk, high reward. Are you sure you want to choose this class? I clicked yes. I didn't care about difficulty or risk or reward. I just wanted to be something that understood darkness, something that knew what it was like to live in the shadows.",
    "The headset felt heavy on my head when I put it on. Heavy in a way that suggested quality, not weight. The material was soft against my skin, the fit perfect. Dad had researched this, I realized. He'd found the best headset, the most comfortable one, the one that would feel like it wasn't there at all. He'd done this for me, even though he'd never told me.",
    "I lay back on my bed and closed my eyes and waited for the transition. The manual said it would take a moment for the neural interface to synchronize with my brain. I felt a tingling sensation, like pins and needles, but pleasant. Then the darkness behind my eyelids began to lighten, and I felt myself being pulled somewhere else.",
    "The transition was seamless. One moment I was in my apartment, lying on my bed. The next moment I was standing in a virtual world, surrounded by sights and sounds that felt more real than reality. The air smelled like pine and earth. The ground felt solid beneath my feet. The sky was a perfect blue, with clouds that drifted lazily across it. I was in Endless Realms.",
    "The first thing I noticed was the silence. Not the absence of sound, but the absence of the wrong kind of sound. No traffic, no construction, no neighbors' televisions. Just the wind in the trees, the distant call of birds, the gentle rustle of leaves. It was peaceful in a way the real world never was.",
    "The second thing I noticed was the beauty. The landscape stretched out before me—rolling hills, dense forests, distant mountains. Everything was rendered with a level of detail that made the real world look like a low-resolution texture. The colors were vibrant, the lighting perfect, the sense of depth and distance flawless. It was like stepping into a painting.",
    "The third thing I noticed was the loneliness. I was alone in this vast, beautiful world. No other players, no NPCs, no signs of life except the plants and animals. Just me and the endless landscape. It was the same loneliness I felt in the real world, but different. Here, the loneliness felt like a choice. In the real world, it felt like a sentence.",
    "I walked for hours, exploring the world without purpose or direction. I climbed hills and crossed streams and wandered through forests. I saw deer grazing in meadows and birds soaring through the sky. I found a cave with glowing crystals and a waterfall that cascaded into a pool of crystal-clear water. It was beautiful, and it was empty, and I was alone.",
    "The sun began to set, painting the sky in shades of orange and pink. I found a high point and watched the light fade, feeling a sense of peace I hadn't felt in years. The virtual sunset was more beautiful than any real sunset I'd ever seen, but it was also less meaningful. It was just code and graphics, pixels and light. It wasn't real.",
    "Night fell, and the world changed. The sky filled with stars, more stars than I'd ever seen in the real world. The moon rose, casting silver light across the landscape. Creatures emerged from the darkness—glowing insects, howling wolves, things I couldn't identify. The world felt dangerous now, but also alive in a way it hadn't during the day.",
    "I found shelter in a small cave and built a fire using the game's crafting system. The fire crackled and popped, casting warm light against the cave walls. I sat and watched the flames, feeling a strange mix of emotions. Peace and loneliness, wonder and sadness, gratitude and guilt. I was grateful to Dad for this gift, but guilty for enjoying it when Yuna was in a coma.",
    "I logged out as dawn approached. The transition was instant—one moment in the virtual world, the next back in my apartment. The headset felt heavy as I lifted it off my head. The room was dark and quiet and cold. I checked the time—6:47 AM. I'd been in the game for eight hours. Eight hours that had felt like minutes.",
    "I went through my day in a daze. The warehouse, the train, the hospital—everything felt different now. Less real, somehow. The virtual world had been more vivid, more engaging, more alive than the real one. I found myself comparing everything to the game, measuring reality against a virtual standard it couldn't meet.",
    "I visited Yuna at the hospital, but my heart wasn't in it. I sat by her bed and held her hand and talked to her, but my mind was elsewhere. I was thinking about the virtual world, about the sunset I'd watched, about the peace I'd felt. I felt guilty for not being fully present, but I couldn't help it. The game had changed something in me.",
    "I went home and put the headset back on. I didn't think about it. I didn't debate whether I should do it. I just did it. I needed to go back. I needed to feel that peace again. I needed to escape, just for a little while, from the weight that was crushing me.",
    "The second time was easier. The transition was faster, the world more familiar. I knew where I was—near the cave where I'd spent the night. I explored further this time, finding villages and towns and other players. I talked to NPCs and accepted quests and fought monsters. I was playing the game now, not just experiencing it.",
    "I met other players. Some were friendly, some were not. Some were helpful, some were hostile. I formed a party with a group of strangers and we tackled a dungeon together. We fought monsters and solved puzzles and found treasure. It was fun, in a way I hadn't had fun in years. It was distracting, which was what I needed.",
    "I logged out after six hours. The real world felt gray and dull by comparison. The apartment was small and cramped and lonely. The bed was uncomfortable. The silence was oppressive. I lay in the dark and thought about the virtual world, about the friends I'd made, about the adventures I'd had. I wanted to go back.",
    "I fell asleep thinking about the game. I dreamed about it too—vivid, detailed dreams that felt more real than my actual life. I was in the virtual world, exploring and fighting and living. When I woke up, I felt disappointed to be back in reality. That was when I knew I was in trouble.",
    "The third day, I called in sick to work. I didn't feel sick, but I needed to play. I needed to escape. I spent twelve hours in the game, exploring and leveling and making friends. I forgot about Yuna and the hospital and the bills. I forgot about my grief and my guilt and my loneliness. For twelve hours, I was free.",
    "The fourth day, I called in sick again. This time, I did feel sick—sick with guilt and shame and self-loathing. What was I doing? How could I abandon my responsibilities for a game? How could I abandon Yuna? But I couldn't stop. I needed the escape. I needed the peace. I needed to feel something other than pain.",
    "The fifth day, Hiro called. He'd noticed I wasn't at work. He asked if I was okay. I said I was fine, but my voice betrayed me. He knew something was wrong. 'Are you playing?' he asked. I didn't answer. 'You're playing, aren't you?' I still didn't answer. 'It's okay,' he said. 'Everyone's playing. It's okay to need an escape.'",
    "I hung up the phone and put the headset back on. I didn't know if it was okay. I didn't know if escaping was the right thing to do. But I knew I couldn't stop. The game had become something I needed, something I couldn't live without. And that terrified me."
  ];

  const backstoryHeadsetMiddles = [
    "I thought about what Dad would want. He'd bought this for me. He'd spent money he could have used for something else. He'd planned this, whatever this was. If I didn't use it, I was wasting his gift. I was disrespecting his memory. But if I did use it, I was escaping into a virtual world while my sister lay in a coma in the real one. Either way, I was betraying someone. Either way, I was doing it wrong.",
    "The game promised escape. That was its selling point. A world where you could be anyone, do anything, leave your problems behind. But I didn't want to escape. I wanted to fix things. I wanted to wake Yuna up. I wanted to bring Mom and Dad back. I wanted to undo the accident. The game couldn't do any of that. The game was just a distraction, a way to pretend that everything was fine when it wasn't.",
    "I researched the game obsessively. I read every article, watched every video, followed every discussion thread. I learned about the classes and the races and the skills and the world. I learned about the economy and the politics and the social systems. I learned everything there was to know, except what it felt like to actually play. That was the one thing I couldn't learn without logging in.",
    "The headset had a neural interface. That was the revolutionary part. It connected directly to your brain, reading your thoughts and translating them into game actions. No controllers, no keyboards, no buttons. You thought about moving, and you moved. You thought about casting a spell, and you cast it. It was supposed to be seamless, intuitive, like using your own body. The idea terrified me.",
    "I worried about the risks. What if something went wrong? What if the interface damaged my brain? What if I got stuck in the game? What if I couldn't log out? The developers said it was safe, that they'd tested it extensively, that millions of people were using it without problems. But developers always said that. They always said their products were safe until they weren't.",
    "The headset sat on my desk like an accusation. Every time I looked at it, I felt guilty. Guilt for not using it, guilt for wanting to use it, guilt for being alive when my parents weren't. The headset was a physical manifestation of everything I was feeling—grief and guilt and confusion and the overwhelming need to escape from a life that had become unbearable.",
    "I tried to return it. I looked up the return policy, found the receipt, prepared to ship it back. But I couldn't do it. Dad had bought this for me. He'd spent money he didn't have, money that could have gone to Yuna's medical bills, because he thought it would make me happy. Returning it felt like rejecting his love, like saying his gift wasn't good enough. So I kept it.",
    "I tried to sell it. I listed it online, set a price, waited for offers. But I couldn't do that either. Selling Dad's gift felt wrong, like profiting from his death. I took down the listing and put the headset back in its box and tried to forget about it. But I couldn't forget. It was there, on my desk, a constant reminder of everything I'd lost.",
    "I tried to give it away. I thought about Hiro, who would have loved it. I thought about the hospital, maybe they could raffle it off for charity. But I couldn't do that either. The headset was the last thing Dad had ever given me. Giving it away felt like giving away the last piece of him I had left. So I kept it, and I hated myself for keeping it.",
    "The weeks passed, and the headset became part of the landscape of my life. It sat on my desk, gathering dust, while I went through the motions of living. Wake up, work, hospital, home, sleep. Repeat. The headset watched me do it, a silent witness to my slow descent into whatever this was—grief, depression, something in between.",
    "I started talking to it. Not out loud, but in my head. I'd ask it questions, like it could answer. Why did Dad buy this? What did he want me to do with it? Was this his way of telling me to escape? Or was it his way of telling me to live? The headset never answered, of course. It was just plastic and electronics. But asking the questions made me feel less alone.",
    "I started dreaming about it. In my dreams, I'd put on the headset and enter the virtual world, and everything would be different. Yuna would be there, awake and healthy. Mom and Dad would be there, alive and happy. We'd be a family again, exploring this beautiful world together. Then I'd wake up, and the headset would be on my desk, and I'd remember that dreams weren't real.",
    "The breaking point came on a Tuesday. I don't know why Tuesday. Maybe it was just the accumulation of too many bad days. I came home from the hospital after another visit where nothing had changed—Yuna still in the coma, the doctors still saying the same things, the bills still arriving like clockwork. I sat at my desk and looked at the headset and something inside me snapped.",
    "I opened the box. I took out the headset. I put it on my head. I didn't think about it. I didn't debate the pros and cons. I just did it. I needed to escape. I needed to feel something other than this crushing weight. I needed to be somewhere else, anywhere else, even if it was just for a little while.",
    "The transition was instant. One moment I was in my apartment, surrounded by reminders of everything I'd lost. The next moment I was in a virtual world, surrounded by beauty and possibility. The air smelled like pine and earth. The sky was a perfect blue. The ground felt solid beneath my feet. I was in Endless Realms, and for the first time in two years, I didn't feel like I was drowning.",
    "I walked for hours, exploring without purpose or direction. I climbed hills and crossed streams and wandered through forests. I saw deer grazing in meadows and birds soaring through the sky. I found a cave with glowing crystals and a waterfall that cascaded into a pool of crystal-clear water. It was beautiful, and it was empty, and I was alone, and it was perfect.",
    "The sun began to set, painting the sky in shades of orange and pink. I found a high point and watched the light fade, feeling a sense of peace I hadn't felt in years. The virtual sunset was more beautiful than any real sunset I'd ever seen, but it was also less meaningful. It was just code and graphics, pixels and light. It wasn't real. But it felt real, and that was enough.",
    "Night fell, and the world changed. The sky filled with stars, more stars than I'd ever seen in the real world. The moon rose, casting silver light across the landscape. Creatures emerged from the darkness—glowing insects, howling wolves, things I couldn't identify. The world felt dangerous now, but also alive in a way it hadn't during the day.",
    "I found shelter in a small cave and built a fire using the game's crafting system. The fire crackled and popped, casting warm light against the cave walls. I sat and watched the flames, feeling a strange mix of emotions. Peace and loneliness, wonder and sadness, gratitude and guilt. I was grateful to Dad for this gift, but guilty for enjoying it when Yuna was in a coma.",
    "I logged out as dawn approached. The transition was instant—one moment in the virtual world, the next back in my apartment. The headset felt heavy as I lifted it off my head. The room was dark and quiet and cold. I checked the time—6:47 AM. I'd been in the game for eight hours. Eight hours that had felt like minutes.",
    "I went through my day in a daze. The warehouse, the train, the hospital—everything felt different now. Less real, somehow. The virtual world had been more vivid, more engaging, more alive than the real one. I found myself comparing everything to the game, measuring reality against a virtual standard it couldn't meet.",
    "I visited Yuna at the hospital, but my heart wasn't in it. I sat by her bed and held her hand and talked to her, but my mind was elsewhere. I was thinking about the virtual world, about the sunset I'd watched, about the peace I'd felt. I felt guilty for not being fully present, but I couldn't help it. The game had changed something in me.",
    "I went home and put the headset back on. I didn't think about it. I didn't debate whether I should do it. I just did it. I needed to go back. I needed to feel that peace again. I needed to escape, just for a little while, from the weight that was crushing me.",
    "The second time was easier. The transition was faster, the world more familiar. I knew where I was—near the cave where I'd spent the night. I explored further this time, finding villages and towns and other players. I talked to NPCs and accepted quests and fought monsters. I was playing the game now, not just experiencing it.",
    "I met other players. Some were friendly, some were not. Some were helpful, some were hostile. I formed a party with a group of strangers and we tackled a dungeon together. We fought monsters and solved puzzles and found treasure. It was fun, in a way I hadn't had fun in years. It was distracting, which was what I needed.",
    "I logged out after six hours. The real world felt gray and dull by comparison. The apartment was small and cramped and lonely. The bed was uncomfortable. The silence was oppressive. I lay in the dark and thought about the virtual world, about the friends I'd made, about the adventures I'd had. I wanted to go back.",
    "I fell asleep thinking about the game. I dreamed about it too—vivid, detailed dreams that felt more real than my actual life. I was in the virtual world, exploring and fighting and living. When I woke up, I felt disappointed to be back in reality. That was when I knew I was in trouble.",
    "The third day, I called in sick to work. I didn't feel sick, but I needed to play. I spent twelve hours in the game, exploring and leveling and making friends. I forgot about Yuna and the hospital and the bills. I forgot about my grief and my guilt and my loneliness. For twelve hours, I was free.",
    "The fourth day, I called in sick again. This time, I did feel sick—sick with guilt and shame and self-loathing. What was I doing? How could I abandon my responsibilities for a game? How could I abandon Yuna? But I couldn't stop. I needed the escape. I needed the peace. I needed to feel something other than pain.",
    "The fifth day, Hiro called. He'd noticed I wasn't at work. He asked if I was okay. I said I was fine, but my voice betrayed me. He knew something was wrong. 'Are you playing?' he asked. I didn't answer. 'You're playing, aren't you?' I still didn't answer. 'It's okay,' he said. 'Everyone's playing. It's okay to need an escape.'",
    "I hung up the phone and put the headset back on. I didn't know if it was okay. I didn't know if escaping was the right thing to do. But I knew I couldn't stop. The game had become something I needed, something I couldn't live without. And that terrified me.",
    "The headset became my lifeline. I spent more time in the virtual world than the real one. I stopped going to work. I stopped visiting Yuna as often. I stopped caring about bills and responsibilities and the life I was supposed to be living. The virtual world was where I lived now. The real world was just where I slept.",
    "I made friends in the game. Real friends, who understood what I was going through because they were going through it too. We talked about our lives, our problems, our reasons for escaping. We formed a guild, built a base, explored the world together. For the first time in two years, I didn't feel alone.",
    "I leveled up quickly. The Vampire Progenitor class was powerful, and I was good at it. I learned to use my abilities strategically, to fight efficiently, to lead parties. I became known on the server, respected for my skill and my leadership. It felt good to be good at something, to be respected, to matter.",
    "But the guilt never went away. Every time I logged out, I remembered Yuna in the hospital. Every time I logged in, I felt like I was abandoning her. I was trapped between two worlds, unable to fully commit to either. The virtual world offered escape, but the real world demanded responsibility. I couldn't have both, and I couldn't choose.",
    "The headset sat on my desk when I wasn't using it, a constant reminder of the choice I'd made. Dad's gift. Dad's escape. Dad's way of telling me it was okay to not be okay. I touched it sometimes, tracing the smooth curves, wondering what he'd think if he could see me now. Would he be proud? Would he be disappointed? I'd never know.",
    "The neural interface became more natural over time. I stopped thinking about the technology and started just using it. Moving became as easy as thinking. Casting spells became as natural as breathing. The boundary between my mind and the game blurred, until it was hard to tell where I ended and the virtual world began.",
    "I started having trouble distinguishing between the two worlds. I'd reach for things that weren't there. I'd expect to see game interfaces in the real world. I'd forget that I couldn't just log out of my problems. The virtual world was becoming more real than reality, and that scared me.",
    "But I couldn't stop. The game was the only place where I felt peace. The only place where I didn't feel like I was drowning. The only place where I could breathe. So I kept playing, and I kept escaping, and I kept hoping that somehow, someway, this would all make sense in the end."
  ];

